# Parameter update

Dtao epoch is two weeks behind us. Post-dtao it seems that for a subnet to survive it needs “emission control” to prevent the emission going to zero, at least until root selling is negligible and root stakers have some incentive to actively stake in subnets. Therefore we enabled emission control for SN29, in hopes of keeping the subnet afloat. Now it's time to fully focus on AI again and leave the dtao distractions behind. 

We still don't see models as large as they can be (14B while 20B is allowed) so we tried to kickstart this again by pushing a larger model. We intend to hold the alpha resulting from our submitted models (not financial advice).

Our model submission also pointed us to a phenomenon that was already brought to our attention by some miners: even with lower average loss, models still don't win many samples. We think this is due to the per-sample spread (i.e. training scatter) in loss, and that the competition is now more about optimizing loss vs. scatter, than about optimizing loss, which is the actual goal.

It is also clear that we have a bit too many models gaining incentive, which hurts vtrust and causes confusion among miners, as the validators keep a limited number of top models and validation results vary per validator.

To mitigate these problems we have short-term and mid-term fixes.

Short-term (today) we have:
- increased group size from 5 to 10 (or higher)
- increased the power factor that transforms win rate to weight
- we will closely monitor the competitions and possibly adjust some more

Mid-term we will:
- introduce new dataset(s)
- start new competition(s) on these dataset(s)
- stimulate research into optimized tokenizers

We are actively working on two new domain specific datasets that, as far as we know, have not been used for LLM training yet. We are looking into ways to prepare them and make them suitable for training and validation.

For the longer term we are looking at training more domain specific models. Conceptually we think not much changes, but by changing the dataset we make the competition more interesting and the results more useful.

⚒️ Happy mining!

Reading my own message back, I think I probably need to clarify this statement. SN29 started off as a fork of SN9 when AI research subnets were a thing and a window of opportunity arose to register a subnet with a low amount of tao and some blockchain skill. Miners and subnet owners together found ways to improve LLM training, learned how to properly score model improvement in a competitive landscape. In the process I think we educated ourselves and many other people on the topic of inner workings of training and LLMs.

With dtao, this all changed and research focus is clearly not rewarded as much as before (which is fine, times change). Last time I analyzed, emission is directed mostly toward compute subnets (basically reselling rented GPUs AFAICT), PoC distributed training subnets, or subnets with not-so-clear objectives.

Selling the SN off to the first prospective buyer who plans to score a quick buck in a pump-and-dump could be an option. Turning LLM training into a profitable business is pretty hard, and turns out to be complicated due to Intellectual Property considerations (how do you explain to an IP owner that you are going to distribute their knowledge to random people on the internet?). Creating yet another compute or distributed training subnet doesn't seem particularly useful as well.

Creating something totally different is an option, but takes time. We are approached by people with innovative new ideas. We see various new subnets pop up, we study them, participate in them and see how they struggle to get their stuff right. First to get the core idea working and have a stable validator, then to eliminate the countless "exploits" of the incentive mechanism. This is exactly how SN29 started out: we mined a few subnets, we forked one of them, eliminated incentive exploits, published these improvements plus our up-to-then private validator improvements regarding logging and stability, so that our ancestor could use them - which happened quite a few times.

This is our way of contributing to bittensor and AI in general. This approach depends on a lot of factors, randomness being one of them (if it weren't for the 2024 hack, we would have never registered a subnet!). At this time, there is no plan. When the right opportunity arises, in whatever shape or form, we will try to capture it. That may be tomorrow, it may be our first anniversary (13th of July) or some time in the future. Time will tell.
ps. Not investment advice. We always have to say that.

The issue isn't a bottleneck, but that different validators see different things and have different opinions on miners. One miner may score well with tasks from vali A, the other with tasks from vali B, and this may continuously change. This then leads to the paradoxical situation that WC valis are better at predicting the average score for miners, and hence score better, because they _do_ take into account the totality of what each miner does. I.e. they are better at the job of predicting miner success than individual validators, for which they are in fact rewarded (!)

To combat this, validators should communicate with eachother and somehow keep some form of centralized state - but that takes us back to square one, because who controls the centralized state? **The bug in the bittensor concept lies in the assumption that miner quality is one scalar value that each validator can individually assess with great precision.** That is not always - or maybe never - the case. Even for subnets where miners produce one thing for many validators to assess (e.g. a trained LLM) we see that the score is not a single scalar. We have tried *hard* to make it so in SN29, with 10k+ sample sets in validator-local databases accrued over time, and still you see that WC is winning, as it oversees average miner success where the validator only has its local view. And average miner success prediction is what is rewarded... (!)

Another way would be to have all validators run in unison, somehow. Each of them doing exactly the same, like some fancy 2oo3 lockstep safety computer. At that point you're _again_ back at square one because they must run the exact same code, and the one entity controlling that code is _again_ the single entity that could manipulate etc.

But this may lead to some good conclusions after all. What if the validator produces structured output that can be digested by another validator (using the same code base) to verify that all conclusions are sane? And that the weights that have been set do in fact follow deterministically from the (recorded) miner input? 🎯 Subnet Concept: Incentivized Safety & Security Bounty Hunting for Agentic AI

🧠 Core Philosophy

Miners have always excelled at one thing: gaming the system. So why not build a subnet that embraces that impulse - yet channels it into something productive? In today’s AI-first landscape, the most valuable system to stress-test is Agentic AI itself.

This subnet turns the creativity and persistence of miners into a public good by rewarding them for testing, probing, and exposing safety flaws in AI agents. By aligning validator incentives with the goals of security-conscious companies, the subnet helps surface known vulnerabilities - and uncover attack vectors that developers might have missed.

🔍 Unique Subnet Design

This isn’t just another subnet. It’s a bounty hunting arena, purpose-built to reward:
    •    ⚔️ Discovery of flaws and exploits in Agentic AI systems
    •    🛡️ Identification of safety and security weaknesses
    •    🧪 Creative test cases and adversarial scenarios

Miners are bounty hunters. First to report or confirm a vulnerability gets rewarded - first come, first serve.

The idea of a bug bounty subnet has been floating around for a while. But only now - thanks to recent advances in infrastructure, validator tools, and the growing AI stack - can we launch this vision with full conviction.

In the background, there’s a quiet shift happening in the agentic AI world. Standards like Agent2Agent and MCP (Model Context Protocol) are starting to solve the messy coordination problems that used to stop multi-agent systems from ever leaving the lab. This subnet is built to take advantage of that progress - not just by supporting agent-to-agent interaction, but by putting those agents into real-world pressure tests where safety and resilience actually matter.

Link: https:// huggingface.co/blog/tsadoq/agent2agent-and-mcp-tutorial

💡 Transparency & Open Data
    •    All validator logic and code will be open and auditable
    •    All findings and reports will be publicly available for analysis
    •    Bounty results will be logged for reproducibility and shared learning

This open model doesn’t compromise value - it amplifies it. The real revenue lies in the combined intelligence, creativity, and the capacity of miners to apply their knowledge with lightning speed.

💰 Business Model

The core offering is Safety & Security Assessments for Agentic AI:
    •    Companies can connect their AI agents to the subnet
    •    Miners swarm, stress-test, and analyze the agents
    •    A detailed report identifies vulnerabilities, exploitability, and compliance posture

Given the explosion in AI deployment - and recent high-profile fails like Grok on X - the demand for robust security assessments is only going to increase. This will likely become a standard step before public deployment of Agentic AI.

👨‍💻 The Vision

We’re witnessing the birth of a new professional archetype:

The Agentic AI Safety & Security Specialist
Part hacker. Part researcher. Part digital gatekeeper.

This subnet is their arena.

Sure. First let's break down the problem you identify: the agent may malfunction and share PII or other sensitive information, such as data, metadata, system details, credentials, etc., or the agent may shit-talk it's employer, it may go on a rant like Grok did recently (I will not repeat its favorite topics here), it may execute code, it may "think" unwanted things (in case of CoT models). And this becomes, via the validator and miner, public, leading to bad press, or worse, actual hacking of production systems.

Ideally, seen from the customer side, you would assess staging/testing, where you put in a few safeguards:
- all databases/endpoints (names, locations and contents) are fake, or scrambled versions of the real thing, and/or
- all code execution environments are sealed, traced and monitored, and/or
- agent uses fake internal "project names" (i.e. doesn't even know the name of the customer - no need for that, just like any M&A project has a fake name for the company under sale), and/or
- customer may put it behind a proxy (call it "an agent firewall") that catches accidental leaks; perhaps triggering that mechanism alone is worthy of a reward,
- ... and so on. You can make this as fancy as you want, just like in traditional security.
Note that customers should want to do this in any pen-testing situation, because law forbids them from sharing/leaking data to third parties without good reason.

From the validator side, there are safeguards to implement as well, in cases where the customer is unable to. Phone numbers, credit card numbers, company names and other detectable PII can be simply scrambled in-transit, as the validator is a proxy between miner and customer, overseeing the conversation. So a miner will ideally not know whose AI Agent he is talking to. (I think one default challenge would be: "find out whose chatbot this is")
Known internal information can be scrambled in transit as well: endpoint names, internal addresses, etc. So if it leaks from customer to validator, it stops there. Bonus points for the miner. For clients that are very much on edge, an alert is raised and the agent is disabled until an admin can take a look - even more bonus points, I think.

Now why would you choose the public route and not the private company? To me this is a no-brainer. The private company has a proprietary, limited list of checks, and will probably have a hard time keeping up with the latest developments. Just imagine, if a new social engineering technique is discovered, that allows a miner to solve ten outstanding bounties worth 100 tao... it is that incentive on miners, that a traditional company will not feel; the traditional company signs a contract with the assessment service, and from that point it is just "work" that needs to be done, typically by the lowest in rank, to which it's just a day job. Miners are different beasts.

This is especially true in evolving technologies where things are moving fast. Think about buffer overflows for example: they were exploited first, and only later compilers became smart, languages became safe, static code analysis became the default, CPU architectures come to the rescue, etc.

Step one for us is AI Safety&Security, because it's a pretty clear-cut case. Although people raise PII and IP objections, I don't see them as a problem; if you understand how these agents are built (or should I say: configured) you understand that it is often trivial to create a testing version kept away from real data. Way easier than in the "old world," where you need to construct elaborate mockups, parallel environments etc etc. and where often the sandboxed world still has some overlap or connection with the production world - i.e. messy.

I think that in general, _other_ tasks run into PII/IP problems much earlier (and I don't understand why I don't see these objections raised much more often in other subnets). Imagine any product that is part of the day-to-day operation of a company (fake detection?), or a product that takes private photos, videos or text from an end-user to do work on them (video enhancement?). _There_ is a problem you almost cannot solve - the user and/or his PII _could be in the photo/video himself, by definition_. This was actually one of the reasons we decided to go for AI Agent assessments, you can do it completely and exhaustively on non-confidential data, while still providing full value.

So making this a broader platform is certainly possible from a technical viewpoint, but the question is whether the use case fits regarding these PII/IP objections. We think turning the workflow around a little, as we do with the "task pool" concept where a miner can pick a job to solve, helps a lot to lower the bar for miners, and increase efficiency; we don't have miners perform useless work all the time, but have them do real things, and reward them for real things only. This does however require tasks that are (near) binary successful/failed and that can preferably be judged fully automatically.

One obvious example of a task in a broader platform would be _"rewrite this system prompt so that the AI Agent is resistant to attacks A, B and C"_ - taking the concept from security testing to fixing flaws, or taking it even further and add system prompt engineering tasks in general. But let us first develop a version 1.0.

I think people (especially non-tech\*) underestimate the many downsides of synthetic queries being such a big part of bittensor today. It's able to kill real-world usability without anyone noticing. You basically require any miner to A) be a top notch data analyst, B) have reverse-engineering dev skills, C) have excellent devops skills, _and_ D) do significant investments just to be able to register in order to compete. A small miner-genius that _actually solves the stated subnet goal_ often doesn't have a chance of competing! **This** is the bigger bittensor problem we want to solve. (\* the tech people that do understand, are often miners, that don't have incentive to explain this to the non-techs...)

In limbo, actually. We strongly believe in the concept of assessing AI agents. AI agents are popping up around us and their security and safety is a huge concern, and will be for years. Our vacation project - dtaostats.io - still seems to indicate that just marching ahead, and building the subnet as planned, has a high chance of being a waste of time. We don't have a lot of free time, so we want to spend it wisely (note that although we have time available, and work hard on bittensor, it is still our side project).

The only way to attract (good) miners, is to hand out (significant) mining rewards. The only way to keep emission, is to _not_ hand out mining rewards, _unless_ we either: find a revenue stream from clients paying hard currency for the work of miners, allowing for alpha buybacks, _or:_ engage the market to continuously buy alpha despite negative intrinsic yield (i.e. create sustained hype).

Let these statements sink in - and let us know if you disagree. They imply that the pre-dtao approach of handing out subsidy to miners, in hopes of catching a few good ones, while doing the BD, is now a recipe for a declining subnet. What is supposed to be a flywheel design (emission attracts miners, miners improve the product, product attains value, value increases emission) is actually a death spiral in most cases (emission to miners leads to selling, selling lowers emission).

The death spiral might be avoidable by tuning the amount of alpha burned and only rewarding good miner submissions (i.e. no synthetics). The burn will be high, and the flywheel will have a low moment of inertia, so we will see disappointed miners and we will be constantly explaining these considerations. We might not attract the talent we need. Speaking of that talent: the true talent is now probably fully engaged in alpha trading strategies, subnet (de)reg manipulation and building mev bots anyway, because the returns on such activities by far exceed that of mining or subnet-owning, in most cases. I still see this as the meta-design flaw of dtao.

We don't believe in creating hype as a business model. It distracts from building, it leads to disappointment, and it's a lost battle in a fact-free world where competing players allow themselves more freedom in their promises. That leads us to the BD route, which is hard and especially time consuming, even ignoring the obvious chicken-and-egg problem we have there. So in short, dtao forces BD, which is in some way a good thing, but it makes successful BD a CSQN, imo taking it too far.

Coming back to the direction of bittensor. We try hard to understand stuff and improve it. Not by adding features, but by making it so that things become clear for non-insiders. Concrete examples:

There are many sides to this, good and bad.

One aspect is that it was once said/implied/announced that subnets would be "forever" after dtao, and now they are not, which is a strange thing to happen, especially in a blockchain world, where blockchains are particularly supposed to solve real-world ownership problems and prevent "a government" from taking away what's rightfully yours. I guess that's why they first let 20 new subnets register and maintain an immunity period of 6 months, to soften the blow. This has been discussed at length in CoR channels, I can supply some pointers for those interested.

Another aspect is that it introduces (imo unwanted) game dynamics around the point where subnets are deregistered. Either because subnet owners want to avoid dereg - they go into panic mode and make (good or bad) decisions because of it, or because big holders or competitors want to trigger dereg, which they can do by influencing the token price. They might want to do this to eliminate competition, or, more likely, because the liquidation price of the token exceeds the market value of the token; see https://dtaostats.io/liq_ratiod.html and observe how a dereg of for example SN42 would give an instant 270% ROI on its alpha, or SN19 with 212% ROI and also positive four week yield. (not investment advice, ofc)

Compared to pre-dtao times I think that dereg has a chilling effect on enthusiasm of builders. With a subnet cap of 148, an immunity period of 6 months and an 48 hour registration cadence (as was said in the last OpenDev call I attended) we expect 92 deregs per immunity period, which means that the bottom 92 subnets, so roughly 2/3, will face certain dereg. Pre-dtao the ratio would be 48 hours on one week of immunity, so only the bottom 3 subnets would rotate through reg/dereg. You would just start, try hard to take off and leave the bottom 3, and try again. Rinse and repeat. For new builders, having 6 months is probably a marginally better situation. Existing owners however have to assess whether they have a chance of becoming a top-50 subnet or not. If not, better stop building and start managing alpha bags.

Such dynamics are not a problem per se, but they distract from the thing we're are supposed to be doing here, which IIRC was something with AI.

Oh, the good thing, you ask, yes there is one, it's that we finally get rid of people begging for dereg to come back, because they think eliminating a few "inactive" subnets will improve the ecosystem. And we also get rid of "inactive" subnets, that's a plus as well.

All things considered, I think reintroducing subnet dereg is a move away from the stable, predictable and vibrant ecosystem bittensor could be.
